olitical science, economics, and history to provide a fresh answer to this question. While scholarly tradition points to the colonial origin of a country’s legal system as the most important determinant of the health of its financial system, this volume points instead to a country’s political institutions—its governmental structures and the rules of the political game—as the key. Specifically, the openness and competitiveness of a country’s political system tends to reflect itself in the openness and competitiveness of its financial system.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economic History.2bisacsh1 aBarth, James R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaprio, Gerard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGourevitch, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaber, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaber, Stephen, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKeefer, Philip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLevine, Ross, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMusacchio, Aldo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNorth, Douglass C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNorth, Douglass C., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aShinn, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShirley, Mary M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSummerhill, William R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSylla, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWallis, John Joseph, econtributor.